  <div class="sc-page">
    <a href="/" class="sc-back">← stanwood.dev</a>

    <div class="sc-hero">
      <img
        src="/images/ship-clock.webp"
        alt="A wall clock above a developer's desk with code on screen"
        loading="eager"
        decoding="async"
        width="960"
        height="540"
      />
    </div>

    <div class="sc-intro">
      <h1 class="sc-intro-title">Ship Clock</h1>
      <p class="sc-intro-sub">stanwood.dev · production deploy tracker</p>
      <p class="sc-intro-desc">One number on the wall. Days since this site last shipped — no spin, no excuses. Updates every five minutes from Vercel.</p>
    </div>

    <ShipClockApp client:idle />

    <!-- Cadence ladder -->
    <div class="sc-cadence">
      <h2 class="sc-cadence-heading">The Cadence Ladder</h2>
      <p class="sc-cadence-sub">how to read your number · five tiers</p>

      <div class="sc-tier-list">
        <div class="sc-tier sc-tier--hot">
          <div class="sc-tier-days">0d</div>
          <div class="sc-tier-body">
            <span class="sc-tier-label">shipped today 🚀</span>
            <p class="sc-tier-text">In the zone. Daily-driver project — every day is a build day.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-tier sc-tier--good">
          <div class="sc-tier-days">1–3d</div>
          <div class="sc-tier-body">
            <span class="sc-tier-label">fresh off the line</span>
            <p class="sc-tier-text">Active development. Healthy side-project rhythm — most indie shippers live here.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-tier sc-tier--warn">
          <div class="sc-tier-days">4–6d</div>
          <div class="sc-tier-body">
            <span class="sc-tier-label">clock is ticking</span>
            <p class="sc-tier-text">Between sprints. Not bad — but block out a shipping day before momentum slips.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-tier sc-tier--cool">
          <div class="sc-tier-days">1–2w</div>
          <div class="sc-tier-body">
            <span class="sc-tier-label">getting rusty</span>
            <p class="sc-tier-text">Probably waiting on a decision or a review. A typo fix or version bump resets the clock — momentum compounds.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-tier sc-tier--bad">
          <div class="sc-tier-days">14d+</div>
          <div class="sc-tier-body">
            <span class="sc-tier-label">dust is collecting</span>
            <p class="sc-tier-text">Abandonment risk. Even a README polish counts — ship something, anything, today.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="sc-cadence-note">Status labels match the counter above. The 28-day grid shows your real cadence — gaps speak louder than the headline number.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Unstick the clock -->
    <div class="sc-unstick">
      <h2 class="sc-unstick-heading">When the clock is high</h2>
      <p class="sc-unstick-sub">five common reasons · the smallest move that resets it</p>

      <div class="sc-unstick-list">
        <div class="sc-unstick-row sc-unstick-row--scope">
          <div class="sc-unstick-head">
            <span class="sc-unstick-num">01</span>
            <span class="sc-unstick-label">scope keeps growing</span>
          </div>
          <p class="sc-unstick-symptom">The PR has been open for days. Every fix uncovers another. You can't ship until the whole thing is right.</p>
          <p class="sc-unstick-fix"><span class="sc-unstick-fix-label">fix</span>Cut a tracer-bullet — the smallest slice that proves the path. Stub the rest behind a feature flag, deploy, then layer in. Shipping a quarter beats sitting on the whole.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="sc-unstick-row sc-unstick-row--review">
          <div class="sc-unstick-head">
            <span class="sc-unstick-num">02</span>
            <span class="sc-unstick-label">waiting on a review</span>
          </div>
          <p class="sc-unstick-symptom">PR's been sitting for two days. The reviewer's busy. You're blocked on the main work.</p>
          <p class="sc-unstick-fix"><span class="sc-unstick-fix-label">fix</span>Ship a side fix — a typo, a README polish, a dep bump. The clock resets while the big PR waits, and you stay in the habit.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="sc-unstick-row sc-unstick-row--spread">
          <div class="sc-unstick-head">
            <span class="sc-unstick-num">03</span>
            <span class="sc-unstick-label">spread too thin</span>
          </div>
          <p class="sc-unstick-symptom">Three projects, all half-done. You context-switch every hour. Nothing crosses the finish line.</p>
          <p class="sc-unstick-fix"><span class="sc-unstick-fix-label">fix</span>Pick one for the day and ignore the rest. A 10-line PR on the chosen project counts. Tomorrow you can switch — but ship one thing today.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="sc-unstick-row sc-unstick-row--perfect">
          <div class="sc-unstick-head">
            <span class="sc-unstick-num">04</span>
            <span class="sc-unstick-label">it's not ready yet</span>
          </div>
          <p class="sc-unstick-symptom">Works locally, but the copy isn't right, the empty state's ugly, and you found one more edge case. So the branch sits another night.</p>
          <p class="sc-unstick-fix"><span class="sc-unstick-fix-label">fix</span>Ship behind a flag. Out the door, off by default — production-shaped feedback beats local polish, and the clock thanks you.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="sc-unstick-row sc-unstick-row--debt">
          <div class="sc-unstick-head">
            <span class="sc-unstick-num">05</span>
            <span class="sc-unstick-label">old code in the way</span>
          </div>
          <p class="sc-unstick-symptom">You can't add the new thing because the old thing is tangled. You keep planning the rewrite. Nothing ships.</p>
          <p class="sc-unstick-fix"><span class="sc-unstick-fix-label">fix</span>Ship a deletion. Removing dead code is a deploy too — same green tick, same clock reset. Subtraction is shipping.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="sc-unstick-foot">The pattern across all five: the move that unsticks you is smaller than you think. Whatever lands today wins.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Cadences in the wild -->
    <div class="sc-wild">
      <h2 class="sc-wild-heading">Cadences in the wild</h2>
      <p class="sc-wild-sub">six teams · how their clocks tick</p>
      <p class="sc-wild-intro">Your number isn't right or wrong — it depends on what you ship. Continuous deployment makes sense for a web service and would be malpractice for a spacecraft. Six well-known cadences, slowest to fastest, to triangulate against.</p>

      <div class="sc-wild-list">
        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--blazing">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">11s</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">per deploy</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Amazon</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">continuous · web</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">A 2011 internal talk put production deploys at roughly <strong>one every 11 seconds</strong> across all services — about 130,000/day. Each commit ships behind its own pipeline and rolls back automatically if a metric drifts.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--fast">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">~50</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">per day</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Etsy</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">continuous · marketplace</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">Wrote the playbook the rest of the industry copied. <strong>50+ deploys a day</strong> from a single trunk branch, fronted by the "Deployinator" — anyone in engineering can press the button.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--steady">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">4</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">weeks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Google Chrome</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">release train · browser</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">Stable channel cuts every <strong>four weeks</strong> since 2021 (was six since 2010). Anything that misses the train waits for the next one — features are flag-gated behind it.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--cycle">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">~9</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">weeks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Linux kernel</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">merge windows · OS</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">Torvalds runs a <strong>two-week merge window</strong> followed by ~seven weeks of release candidates. Mainline lands every nine or ten weeks; the daily commit volume in between is enormous.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--annual">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">1</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">year</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Apple iOS</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">tentpole · mobile OS</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">A major version every September, walking out of the Steve Jobs Theater. Point releases fill the year (.1, .2, .3 every month or two), but the headline number only moves once — keynote-shaped cadence.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="sc-wild-card sc-wild-card--glacial">
          <div class="sc-wild-stat">
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-num">~10</span>
            <span class="sc-wild-stat-unit">years</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sc-wild-body">
            <div class="sc-wild-head">
              <span class="sc-wild-name">Voyager 1</span>
              <span class="sc-wild-tag">remote patch · spacecraft</span>
            </div>
            <p class="sc-wild-text">Launched 1977, still flying. NASA last patched the flight software in <strong>2024</strong> when a chip failed 15 billion miles out — a one-way uplink that takes 22 hours to arrive. Roughly one code drop per decade.</p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="sc-wild-foot">The right cadence is the one your blast radius can absorb. Etsy ships 50/day because a bad checkout commit reverts in three minutes. Voyager ships once a decade because the round-trip light delay is two days and the original team is mostly retired. Match the clock to the cost of being wrong.</p>
    </div>

    <RepoTracker client:idle />

    <!-- How it works / build your own -->
    <div class="sc-explainer">
      <h2 class="sc-explainer-heading">Build Your Own</h2>
      <p class="sc-explainer-sub">three steps · ~30 minutes</p>

      <div class="sc-steps">
        <div class="sc-step">
          <span class="sc-step-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <p class="sc-step-title">Create a Vercel read token</p>
            <p class="sc-step-body">In Vercel → Account Settings → Tokens, create a scoped read token. Grab your Project ID from the project settings URL.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-step">
          <span class="sc-step-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <p class="sc-step-title">Call the deployments API</p>
            <p class="sc-step-body">One fetch pulls the last 25 production deploys with commit metadata attached. The rest is arithmetic.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-step">
          <span class="sc-step-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <p class="sc-step-title">Mount a counter component</p>
            <p class="sc-step-body">Compute <code>daysSince</code> from <code>deployments[0].created</code> and display it. Poll every 5 minutes with a <code>setInterval</code> or use stale-while-revalidate caching.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sc-code-block" id="sc-snippet"><span class="sc-code-comment">// GET /api/ship-clock</span>
<span class="sc-code-key">const</span> <span class="sc-code-var">url</span> = &#96;<span class="sc-code-str">https://api.vercel.com/v6/deployments</span>
<span class="sc-code-str">  ?projectId=&#36;&#123;</span><span class="sc-code-var">VERCEL_PROJECT_ID</span><span class="sc-code-str">&#125;</span>
<span class="sc-code-str">  &amp;target=production&amp;limit=25&amp;state=READY</span>&#96;;

<span class="sc-code-key">const</span> <span class="sc-code-var">res</span> = <span class="sc-code-key">await</span> fetch(<span class="sc-code-var">url</span>, &#123;
  headers: &#123; Authorization: &#96;<span class="sc-code-str">Bearer &#36;&#123;</span><span class="sc-code-var">VERCEL_TOKEN</span><span class="sc-code-str">&#125;</span>&#96; &#125;
&#125;);

<span class="sc-code-key">const</span> &#123; deployments &#125; = <span class="sc-code-key">await</span> <span class="sc-code-var">res</span>.json();
<span class="sc-code-key">const</span> <span class="sc-code-var">lastDeploy</span> = <span class="sc-code-key">new</span> Date(deployments[0].created);
<span class="sc-code-key">const</span> <span class="sc-code-var">daysSince</span> = Math.floor(
  (Date.now() - <span class="sc-code-var">lastDeploy</span>.getTime()) / 86400000
);</div>

      <button class="sc-copy-btn" id="sc-copy-btn">copy snippet</button>

      <p class="sc-explainer-note">
        Works with any Vercel project. Swap in GitHub Actions or Fly.io by adapting the deployment source.<br>
        Commit metadata (message, SHA, PR number) lives in <code>deployments[0].meta</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    const btn = document.getElementById('sc-copy-btn');
    const snippet = document.getElementById('sc-snippet');
    if (btn && snippet) {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const code = `// GET /api/ship-clock
const url = \`https://api.vercel.com/v6/deployments?projectId=\${VERCEL_PROJECT_ID}&target=production&limit=25&state=READY\`;

const res = await fetch(url, {
  headers: { Authorization: \`Bearer \${VERCEL_TOKEN}\` }
});

const { deployments } = await res.json();
const lastDeploy = new Date(deployments[0].created);
const daysSince = Math.floor(
  (Date.now() - lastDeploy.getTime()) / 86400000
);`;
        navigator.clipboard.writeText(code).then(() => {
          btn.textContent = 'copied!';
          setTimeout(() => { btn.textContent = 'copy snippet'; }, 2000);
        });
      });
    }
  </script>
